The customer is about to pick one of four boxes, each with an initial 1/4 chance of being defective. The clerk randomly opens one box and finds it good. This action provides new information: the opened box is definitely good, leaving three boxes. 

Using conditional probability, the probability that any specific remaining box is defective is recalculated. Initially, each box had a 1/4 chance. After one good box is removed, the probability redistributes equally among the remaining three boxes. Each of these boxes now has a 1/3 chance of being defective.

**Answer:** \boxed{\text{Any of the remaining three boxes}}
